1 (3) a copycat weapon.
2 (e) “Binary trigger system” means a device that, when installed in or attached to
3 a firearm, fires both when the trigger is pulled and on release of the trigger.
4 (f) “Bump stock” means a device that, when installed in or attached to a firearm,
5 increases the rate of fire of the firearm by using energy from the recoil of the firearm to
6 generate a reciprocating action that facilitates repeated activation of the trigger.
7 (g) “Burst trigger system” means a device that, when installed in or attached to a
8 firearm, allows the firearm to discharge two or more shots with a single pull of the trigger
9 by altering the trigger reset.
10 (H) “CONVERTIBLE PISTOL” MEANS ANY SEMIAUTOMATIC PISTOL THAT
11 CAN BE CONVERTED INTO A MACHINE GUN SOLELY BY THE ATTACHMENT OF A
12 SWITCH/AUTO–SEAR.
13 [(h)] (I) (1) “Copycat weapon” means:
14 (i) a semiautomatic centerfire rifle that can accept a detachable
15 magazine and has any two of the following:
16 1. a folding stock;
17 2. a grenade launcher or flare launcher; or
18 3. a flash suppressor;
19 (ii) a semiautomatic centerfire rifle that has a fixed magazine with
20 the capacity to accept more than 10 rounds;
21 (iii) a semiautomatic centerfire rifle that has an overall length of less
22 than 29 inches;
23 (iv) a semiautomatic pistol with a fixed magazine that can accept
24 more than 10 rounds;
25 (v) a semiautomatic shotgun that has a folding stock; or
26 (vi) a shotgun with a revolving cylinder.
27 (2) “Copycat weapon” does not include an assault long gun or an assault
28 pistol.

4 HOUSE BILL 1287
1 [(i)] (J) “Detachable magazine” means an ammunition feeding device that can
2 be removed readily from a firearm without requiring disassembly of the firearm action or
3 without the use of a tool, including a bullet or cartridge.
4 [(j)] (K) “Flash suppressor” means a device that functions, or is intended to
5 function, to perceptibly reduce or redirect muzzle flash from the shooter’s field of vision.
6 [(k)] (L) “Hellfire trigger” means a device that, when installed in or attached to
7 a firearm, disengages the trigger return spring when the trigger is pulled.
8 [(l)] (M) “Licensed firearms dealer” means a person who holds a dealer’s license
9 under Title 5, Subtitle 1 of the Public Safety Article.
10 [(m)] (N) (1) “Rapid fire activator” means any device, including a removable
11 manual or power–driven activating device, constructed so that, when installed in or
12 attached to a firearm:
13 (i) the rate at which the trigger is activated increases; or
14 (ii) the rate of fire increases.
15 (2) “Rapid fire activator” includes a bump stock, trigger crank, hellfire
16 trigger, binary trigger system, burst trigger system, switch/auto–sear, or a copy or a similar
17 device, regardless of the producer or manufacturer.
18 (3) “Rapid fire activator” does not include a semiautomatic replacement
19 trigger that improves the performance and functionality over the stock trigger.
20 [(n)] (O) “Switch/auto–sear” means a device that applies force to a firearm’s
21 trigger bar to prevent it from limiting the weapon to firing only one round each time the
22 trigger is depressed.
23 [(o)] (P) “Trigger crank” means a device that, when installed in or attached to a
24 firearm, repeatedly activates the trigger of the firearm through the use of a crank, a lever,
25 or any other part that is turned in a circular motion.
26 4–305.2.
27 A PERSON MAY NOT MANUFACTURE, SELL, OFFER FOR SALE, PURCHASE,
28 RECEIVE, OR TRANSFER A CONVERTIBLE PISTOL.
29 4–306.
30 (a) Except as otherwise provided in this subtitle, a person who violates this
31 subtitle is guilty of a misdemeanor and on conviction is subject to imprisonment not
32 exceeding 3 years or a fine not exceeding $5,000 or both.

